title: Support to allow user to specify compute stream per session
body:
Create computation cuda stream explicitly rather than use default legacy stream or per-thread default stream.

CUDA has two kinds of default stream. One is called legacy default stream. The other is called per-thread default stream which was introduced since CUDA 7. Here are details: https://devblogs.nvidia.com/gpu-pro-tip-cuda-7-streams-simplify-concurrency/

At beginning, CUDA EP was implemented with per-thread default stream. But, cudnn, cublas were still execute on legacy stream. That is to say, handcrafted CUDA kernels in ORT are running on per-thread stream, but cudnn/cublas kernels are running on legacy stream. And implicitly, these two streams are synchronized. During training development, we found that this synchronization caused overhead. For example, for BERT-L training, forcing all kernels to one stream will increase training throughput about 8%. For inference, we saw latency decrease too. 

Due to time constraint, per-thread default stream was disabled and instead legacy default stream was enabled in current CUDA EP.

The below are what this PR addresses.
1. Allow users to specify the stream they want to use through OrtCUDAProviderOptions. That is to say, with the current implementation, the users can specify the stream per ORT session. Later, we may improve it to allow user to specify stream per ORT run call.
2. If users don't specify the stream, then ORT will create a compute stream explicitly by calling cudaStreamCreateWithFlags with cudaStreamNonBlocking, which means compute stream in ORT won't synchronize with legacy default stream. The plan is that after this PR, we should not use legacy default stream or per-thread default stream anymore. Instead, all of GPU kernels should be launched in this compute stream. That is to say, for every handcrafted CUDA kernel in ORT, we need to explicitly specify which stream to launch it.

title: Fix flaky test and avoid divide by zero in SoftmaxCrossEntropyLoss-CPU.
body:
The change fixes two issues that were caught as _flaky_ test:

1. **Invalid label data being passed into tests**
    - `random.Uniform` returns values that are outside the range [a, b) because of `float` to `int64` cast internally due to the usage of `uniform_real_distribution` that expects template type of floating types only. This results in index out of bounds exception when we use `uniform_real_distribution` with `std::default_random_engine` and perform an explicit cast from `float` to `int64`. We must have an overload of  `random.Uniform` that uses `uniform_int_distribution` to prevent the need for such a cast.

2. **SoftmaxCrossEntropyLoss-CPU dividing by zero**
    - One of the test was exercising the scenario where all label values were `0` and `ignore_index` was also `0` hence the loss should also be zero since all values should be dropped. On GPU the kernel correctly calculated loss as zero but on CPU it ended up dividing sum of all losses (zero) by zero which resulted in -nan.

Interestingly, both the tests ran fine on Windows even when I ran them in a loop for 100 times. In the hindsight, it seems this issue also existed in _GatherGradOpTest.Gather_axis1_float_impl2_ and _GatherGradOpTest.Gather_axis0_float_impl2_ that I have fixed as part of this PR.

title: Function expansion support/bug fixes and Upgrade ONNX submodule to 1.7 release candidate 1.
body:
Motivation for this change:
  - In preparation for ORT 1.3 release we must make it compliant with ONNX 1.7.
  - Function expansion support for functions that require context and bug fixes in this area that were failing most ONNX function expansion test.
    - Prerequisite for ORT 1.3 release to be compliant with functions.
    - **Needed as part of this commit because function expansion changes enables code paths require correct spec (comes with this ONNX update) and ONNX update has tests that depend on function expansion update.**
  - Dropout(12) forward/backward kernel needs `training_mode` update that comes as part of this update.

**I expect one more commit to go into ONNX 1.7 that will either remove GraphCall or move it under _experimental_ domain (see https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2741), subsequently, there _will_ be another ONNX submodule update PR that will use commit from ONNX 1.7 release branch.** Until then lets start the work to move to ONNX 1.7 and iron out any issues as several ops were removed.

title: Use cublasHgemm "back" for fp16 computation with Volta GPU
body:
**Description**: Use cublasHgemm for fp16 computation with Volta GPU

cublasHgemm  is used for  fp16 computation with Volta GPU before training code is merged into master. For historical reasons when we did master->old training branch internally merge, we commented out that path. So I used "back" in PR title to indicate this change is just re-enable existing path.

This change should do no harm for inference because it is the case already in master before training is merged. 
This change bring perf improvement on training, tested on 32GV100. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/80714938-37d6d400-8b28-11ea-9039-c07fd017a2f0.png)

The reasons exists here https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cublas/index.html#cublassetmathmode. 
cublasGemmEx's computation type is CUDA_R_32F, though its main data inputs.outputs are CUDA_R_16F. cublasHgemm did CUDA_R_16F computation. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Function expansion support and Update ONNX to 1.7 release candidate 1.
body:
Motivation for this change:
  - In preparation for ORT 1.3 release we must make it compliant with ONNX 1.7.
  - Function expansion support for functions that require context and bug fixes in this area that were failing most ONNX function expansion test.
    - Prerequisite for ORT 1.3 release to be compliant with functions.
    - **Needed as part of this commit because function expansion changes enables code paths require correct spec (comes with this ONNX update) and ONNX update has tests that depend on function expansion update.**
  - Dropout(12) forward/backward kernel needs `training_mode` update that comes as part of this update.

**I expect one more commit to go into ONNX 1.7 that will either remove GraphCall or move it under _experimental_ domain (see https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2741), subsequently, there _will_ be another ONNX submodule update PR that will use commit from ONNX 1.7 release branch.** Until then lets start the work to move to ONNX 1.7 and iron out any issues as several ops were removed.

title: Modify Pipeline Facilities to Fix PipeDream Deadlock
body:
In our current design, one pipeline stage may compute
`Wait->Recv->FW->Send->Record`
and then
`Wait->Recv->BW->Send->Record`
However, this may have a deadlock. To resolve it, we need to do
`Wait->Recv->Wait->FW->Record->Send->Record`
and then
`Wait->Recv->Wait->BW->Record->Send->Record`

This PR changes pipeline transformation for adding extra `Wait`s and `Record`s. In addition, to avoid another GPU deadlock, we move `Send` and `Recv` to CPU completely. We also fix the shape inference in `WaitEvent`/`RecordEvent`. It wrongly passed **unknown shape** to **scalar shape** from input to output.

title: Stop proceeding with constant folding if a CPU kernel is not found found
body:
Constant folding assumes that every node in the graph will have a CPU kernel which is strictly not true as we only support a subset of types in some CPU kernels. In those cases, we cannot constant fold and stop.

Fix #3735
